<br>
Rain spells do NOT resist more than other spells!<br>
Ok, got Sirocco (mage rain spell), tried it out on greenies to test..<br>
resists..<br>
hm..<br>
tried several times...<br>
resists...<br>
<br>
Seem familar?<br>
<br>
Ah, but! Tonight, not resisted very often! You know why?<br>
The more often you cast a spell the less it gets resisted !!! (up to a point)<br>
<br>
Remember that experience with your first Uber Nuke, Cinder Bolt. First few casts resisted like crazy, didn't they?<br>
Because rains are tricky to use and mana expensive, we don't use them much, ergo resists are crap.<br>
<br>
Tonight a small train at Karnors, I dropped Sirocco on a dog and a ghosty, BAM! 4 waves did 630 hp, xp twice, mwahah!<br>
<br>
What I did was sit in EC while trading, casting Sirocco on greenies, to get the number of casts of Sirocco up.<br>
<br>
Still not a spell to use round chanters and in areas with mobs above/below you, but other than that, despite being a conjuration specialist, it RULES! If you can time it right mobs get hammered so quick they don't get time to Gate/heal/run  <br>
<br>
Oh and Malosi (resist debuff) anyway just to make sure! <br>
<br>
TWO RAIN WHAM BAM COMBO<br>
<br>
Ok this would work best for Evocation specialists, or when two mages are working together (or mage/wizzies)<br>
<br>
You need the mobs stationary so stunned/rooted with air earth pet, or mobs fixed due to aggroing on tanks.<br>
<br>
What you do is mem and unload TWO rain spells. A lighter one then a heavier one.<br>
With me Rain of Swords then Sirocco. RoS takes longer to cast so I cast it at start of fight perhaps. less damage = less aggro so mob stays in the rain. Then drop Sirocco on its head. So thats 360hpx3 then 630hpx3.<br>
Can you say; &quot;Make my day, Jibober!&quot; mwahaha!<br>
<br>
You can take it in turns with ally to Malosi. Wizards LOVE this because with pet to root or hold mob and you malosing their rains slice mobs like cheese.<br>
<br>
I'd love to see two mages with Manastorm and Sirocco try this!! *boggles* <p><p align=center><font size=4><b>I'd rather be a Fool who Believes in Dragons, than a king who believes in Nothing</b></font><br>
